This is an attempt at increasing cohesion in the IAST instrumentations. The current strategy to do taint propagation goes like this:

1. A class with call site advice is created on the dd-java-agent/instrumentation/xxx module. It looks like this:
```java
@CallSite(spi = IastAdvice.class)
public class StringCallSite {
  @CallSite.After("java.lang.String java.lang.String.concat(java.lang.String)")
  public static String afterConcat(
      @CallSite.This final String self,
      @CallSite.Argument final String param,
      @CallSite.Return final String result) {
    InstrumentationBridge.onStringConcat(self, param, result);
    return result;
  }
}
  ```
 (A call to this static method is injected into the call site, i.e. the advice is not inlined).
2. There is a call on a method on the `InstrumentationBridge` class. This is a boot cl class, defined in the internal-api module. The method in question looks like like this:
```java
public static void onStringConcat(final String self, final String param, final String result) {
  try {
    if (MODULE != null) {
      MODULE.onStringConcat(self, param, result);
    }
  } catch (final Throwable t) {
    onUnexpectedException("Callback for onStringConcat threw.", t);
  }
}
```
`MODULE` here being a static field of type `IastModule` (another boot class).
3. Add `onStringConcat` to the `IastModule` interface (also defined in internal-api).
4. Now implement `onStringConcat` on the implementation of `IastModule`, named — unsurprisingly — `IastModuleImpl`. This class lives in the dd-java-agent:agent-iast module.
5. Add tests on all three modified modules.

The motivation here is to improve modularity. All the code changes should be limited to the dd-java-agent:instrumentation:xxx module in question.

The basic idea of this solution is that instead of going to the `InstrumentationBridge` boot class, the advice methods (`StringCallSite#afterConcat` in the example above) obtain a reference to the tainting method (implemented `IastModuleImpl#onStringConcat` in the example) through an invokedynamic call. This sidesteps any visibility issues resulting from the tainting method being loaded in the datadog classloader.

The bootstrap method of the invokedynamic call is implemented in a bootstrap classloader class named `CallSiteHelperRegistry`. When IAST starts, it registers in this class all of the tainting methods (called "call site helpers" for a lack of better naming). It looks for them by looking at methods annotated with `@CallSiteHelper` inside classes implementing the marker interface `CallSiteHelperContainer`.

Step one from the status quo description is unchanged; `StringCallSite` in the example above would look the same. However, its invokestatic call needs to be changed to an appropriate invokedynamic call. This is done with a compile time instrumentation implemented in `CsiAdviceTransformationPlugin`.

